<DOC><DOCNO> AP890320-0188 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2043EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-20 0406</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0415</SECOND><HEAD>Blizzard in Kansas; Storms Move Into Southwest, Northeast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Wintry weather lingered throughout much of the country Monday onthe first day of spring, with a blizzard hitting parts of Kansas andstormy weather moving into much of the Southwest and Northeast.   Snow and high winds in western Kansas reduced visibility to nearzero at times, closing Interstate 70 west of Oakley. A high windwarning was issued for west central and southwestern Kansas.   A high wind warning also was posted for northwestern Texas, and awinter storm warning for the south Texas plains. A snow advisory wasissued for the Permian Basin of Texas and for southeastern Coloradoand the Oklahoma panhandle.   A winter storm watch also was posted for much of New Mexico.   Further to the east, strong thunderstorms raked southeast Texasand western Louisiana, and rain extended from the central plainsthrough the Ohio Valley and the Tennessee Valley to the Appalachians.   Although spring officially began at 10:28 a.m. EST Monday, awinter-like storm was brewing in the Northeast.   Snow in the lower Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio Valleywas expected to spread northeastward during the night. A winterweather advisory was posted for the mountains and southwesternsections of Pennsylvania, with winter storm watches posted for awide area ranging from Maine through New Hampshire, Vermont andupstate New York.   A snow advisory was posted for northern Indiana.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 12degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 92 degrees at McAllen, Texas.   The national weather forecast for Tuesday called for rain fromthe Rio Grande Valley of Texas through the Tennessee Valley and thecentral Gulf Coast states to the mid-Atlantic coast, withthunderstorms most likely from the central Gulf Coast to theCarolinas. Snow was expected from the upper Ohio Valley to northernNew England, with rainshowers from the northern and central PacificCoast to northwest Montana. Fair to partly sunny skies were forecastfor the rest of the nation.   High temperatures were expected to remain below 50 from the highplains region to the northern half of the Atlantic coast; in the 20sand lower 30s from the Dakotas through the Great Lakes region tonorthern New England; in the 70s and 80s in southern Arizona,southern and central California and from the central and easternGulf Coast to the southern Atlantic coast.</TEXT></DOC>